import os
import cv2
import numpy as np

labels = ['Non Oil Spill', 'Oil Spill']
img_size = 150

def get_data(data_dir):
    data = []
    for label in labels:
        path = os.path.join(data_dir, label)
        class_num = labels.index(label)
        for img in os.listdir(path):
            try:
                img_arr = cv2.imread(os.path.join(path, img))
                if img_arr is None:
                    print(f"Failed to load image: {img}")
                    continue
                img_arr = img_arr[..., ::-1]  # Convert BGR to RGB
                resized_arr = cv2.resize(img_arr, (img_size, img_size))  # Resizing
                if resized_arr.shape == (img_size, img_size, 3):  # Check shape
                    data.append([resized_arr, class_num])
                else:
                    print(f"Unexpected shape for image {img}: {resized_arr.shape}")
            except Exception as e:
                print(f"Error processing image {img}: {e}")
    return np.array(data, dtype=object)

train = get_data(r"C:\Users\sumee\Downloads\archive (6)\final dataset used for oil spill\dataset-final\dataset\train")
val = get_data(r"C:\Users\sumee\Downloads\archive (6)\final dataset used for oil spill\dataset-final\dataset\Validation")
test = get_data(r"C:\Users\sumee\Downloads\archive (6)\final dataset used for oil spill\dataset-final\dataset\test")

# Initialize empty lists for training, validation, and test datasets
x_train, y_train = [], []
x_val, y_val = [], []
x_test, y_test = [], []

# Populate the training dataset lists
for feature, label in train:
    x_train.append(feature)
    y_train.append(label)

# Populate the validation dataset lists
for feature, label in val:
    x_val.append(feature)
    y_val.append(label)

# Populate the test dataset lists
for feature, label in test:
    x_test.append(feature)
    y_test.append(label)

# Convert lists to numpy arrays and normalize the data by dividing by 255
x_train = np.array(x_train) / 255
x_val = np.array(x_val) / 255
x_test = np.array(x_test) / 255

# Reshape the arrays to the required format for the model (assuming grayscale images)
x_train = x_train.reshape(-1, img_size, img_size, 1)
x_val = x_val.reshape(-1, img_size, img_size, 1)
x_test = x_test.reshape(-1, img_size, img_size, 1)

# Convert label lists to numpy arrays
y_train = np.array(y_train)
y_val = np.array(y_val)
y_test = np.array(y_test)

# Print the shapes of the datasets to verify correct processing
print("x_train:", x_train.shape)
print("y_train:", y_train.shape)
print("x_test:", x_test.shape)
print("y_test:", y_test.shape)
print("x_val:", x_val.shape)
print("y_val:", y_val.shape)

# Initialize the ImageDataGenerator with data augmentation parameters
datagen = ImageDataGenerator(
    rotation_range=90,        # Randomly rotate images up to 90 degrees
    zoom_range=0.5,           # Randomly zoom into images by up to 50%
    width_shift_range=0.2,    # Randomly shift images horizontally by up to 20% of the width
    height_shift_range=0.2,   # Randomly shift images vertically by up to 20% of the height
    horizontal_flip=True      # Randomly flip images horizontally
)

# Reshape the training, validation, and test datasets to have the correct rank (4D)
x_train = np.array(x_train).reshape(2800, 150, 150, 3)  # Reshape for 2800 training samples, 150x150 images, 3 channels (RGB)
x_test = np.array(x_test).reshape(600, 150, 150, 3)     # Reshape for 600 test samples
x_val = np.array(x_val).reshape(600, 150, 150, 3)       # Reshape for 600 validation samples

# Print shapes to verify correct reshaping
print("x_train:", x_train.shape)
print("y_train:", y_train.shape)
print("x_test:", x_test.shape)
print("y_test:", y_test.shape)
print("x_val:", x_val.shape)
print("y_val:", y_val.shape)

# Fit the ImageDataGenerator on the training data to compute any statistics required for the transformations
datagen.fit(x_train)

from keras.layers import BatchNormalization

# Reshape the input data to add a time dimension
x_train = np.array(x_train).reshape(-1, 1, 150, 150, 3)  # (batch_size, time_steps=1, height, width, channels)
x_val = np.array(x_val).reshape(-1, 1, 150, 150, 3)
x_test = np.array(x_test).reshape(-1, 1, 150, 150, 3)

# Print shapes to verify correct reshaping
print("x_train:", x_train.shape)
print("y_train:", y_train.shape)
print("x_test:", x_test.shape)
print("y_test:", y_test.shape)
print("x_val:", x_val.shape)
print("y_val:", y_val.shape)

# Build the Sequential model
model = Sequential()

# Add TimeDistributed Conv2D layer with more filters and Batch Normalization
model.add(TimeDistributed(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu'), input_shape=(1, 150, 150, 3)))
model.add(TimeDistributed(BatchNormalization()))
model.add(TimeDistributed(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2))))

# Add more Conv2D layers with increasing filters
model.add(TimeDistributed(Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu')))
model.add(TimeDistributed(BatchNormalization()))
model.add(TimeDistributed(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2))))

model.add(TimeDistributed(Conv2D(256, (3, 3), activation='relu')))
model.add(TimeDistributed(BatchNormalization()))
model.add(TimeDistributed(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2))))

# Flatten the output before feeding into the LSTM layer
model.add(TimeDistributed(Flatten()))

# Add Dropout to prevent overfitting
model.add(Dropout(0.5))

# Add LSTM layer with more units
model.add(LSTM(128, return_sequences=False))

# Add Dense layer with 2 units and softmax activation for binary classification
model.add(Dense(2, activation='softmax'))

# Compile the model using Adam optimizer with a slightly lower learning rate
model.compile(loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy', optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.0001), metrics=['accuracy'])

model.summary()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Extracting the accuracy and loss values from the training history
acc = history.history['accuracy']
val_acc = history.history['val_accuracy']
loss = history.history['loss']
val_loss = history.history['val_loss']

# Assuming you have test accuracy and loss stored in test_acc and test_loss
test_loss, test_acc = model.evaluate(x_test, y_test, verbose=0)

# Add test accuracy and loss to the list for plotting
acc.append(test_acc)
val_acc.append(test_acc)  # Since we only have one test set, use the same value for consistency
loss.append(test_loss)
val_loss.append(test_loss)

# Update the epochs range to include the test set
epochs_range = range(len(acc))

# Plotting Training, Validation, and Test Accuracy and Loss side by side
plt.figure(figsize=(18, 6))

# Training, Validation, and Test Accuracy

# Load the trained model
model = tf.keras.models.load_model('model.h5')

# Labels corresponding to the classes
labels = ['Non Oil Spill', 'Oil Spill']

def predict_and_show(image_path, img_size=150):
    """
    Predict the class of the image using the loaded model and display the image with its predicted class.
    """
    # Load the image
    img = cv2.imread(image_path)
    
    # Convert the image from BGR to RGB
    img = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)
    
    # Resize the image to the expected input size
    img_resized = cv2.resize(img, (img_size, img_size))
    
    # Normalize the image
    img_normalized = img_resized / 255.0
    
    # Reshape the image to add an extra dimension for the time step
    img_reshaped = np.reshape(img_normalized, (1, 1, img_size, img_size, 3))  # (batch_size, time_steps, height, width, channels)
    
    # Predict the class
    predictions = model.predict(img_reshaped)
    
    # Get the index of the highest probability
    predicted_class_index = np.argmax(predictions, axis=1)[0]
    
    # Get the corresponding class label
    predicted_class = labels[predicted_class_index]
    
    # Display the image with the predicted class label
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 8))
    plt.imshow(img)
    plt.title(f"Predicted: {predicted_class}")
    plt.axis('off')  # Hide the axes
    plt.show()

    print(f"The predicted class is: {predicted_class}")

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, confusion_matrix, roc_curve, auc, precision_recall_curve

def plot_confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred, dataset_name="Dataset"):
    """
    Plot a confusion matrix with a heatmap for the given dataset.
    """
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred)
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt="d", cmap="Blues", xticklabels=['Non Oil Spill', 'Oil Spill'], yticklabels=['Non Oil Spill', 'Oil Spill'])
    plt.title(f"Confusion Matrix for {dataset_name}")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted Label")
    plt.ylabel("True Label")
    plt.show()

def plot_roc_curve(y_true, y_probs, dataset_name="Dataset"):
    """
    Plot the ROC curve for the given dataset.
    """
    fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(y_true, y_probs[:, 1])  # Assuming class 1 is the positive class
    roc_auc = auc(fpr, tpr)
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
    plt.plot(fpr, tpr, color='darkorange', lw=2, label=f'ROC curve (area = {roc_auc:.2f})')
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color='navy', lw=2, linestyle='--')
    plt.xlim([0.0, 1.0])
    plt.ylim([0.0, 1.05])
    plt.xlabel("False Positive Rate")
    plt.ylabel("True Positive Rate")
    plt.title(f"ROC Curve for {dataset_name}")
    plt.legend(loc="lower right")
    plt.show()

def plot_precision_recall_curve(y_true, y_probs, dataset_name="Dataset"):
    """
    Plot the Precision-Recall curve for the given dataset.
    """
    precision, recall, _ = precision_recall_curve(y_true, y_probs[:, 1])  # Assuming class 1 is the positive class
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
    plt.plot(recall, precision, color='purple', lw=2)
    plt.xlabel("Recall")
    plt.ylabel("Precision")
    plt.title(f"Precision-Recall Curve for {dataset_name}")
    plt.show()

def generate_and_plot_reports(x_data, y_data, dataset_name="Dataset"):
    """
    Generate and plot classification report, confusion matrix, ROC curve, and Precision-Recall curve.
    """
    # Make predictions
    predictions = model.predict(x_data)
    pred = np.argmax(predictions, axis=1)
    
    # Print classification report
    print(f"Classification Report for {dataset_name}:")
    print(classification_report(y_data, pred, target_names=['Non Oil Spill', 'Oil Spill']))
    print("\n" + "="*60 + "\n")
    
    # Plot Confusion Matrix
    plot_confusion_matrix(y_data, pred, dataset_name)
    
    # Plot ROC Curve
    plot_roc_curve(y_data, predictions, dataset_name)
    
    # Plot Precision-Recall Curve
    plot_precision_recall_curve(y_data, predictions, dataset_name)

# Generate and plot reports for each dataset
generate_and_plot_reports(x_train, y_train, dataset_name="Training Data")
generate_and_plot_reports(x_val, y_val, dataset_name="Validation Data")
generate_and_plot_reports(x_test, y_test, dataset_name="Test Data")
